%S A210532 3,7,9,15,17,22
%N A210532 Minimum number of observables that need to be measured in order to uniquely determine an n-dimensional quantum state that is known a priori to be pure.
%H A210532 Teiko Heinosaari, Luca Mazzarella, and Michael M. Wolf, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1109.5478">Quantum Tomography under Prior Information</a>. Communications in Mathematical Physics, 318:355-374, 2013.
%F A210532 23 <= a(8) <= 24
%F A210532 4n - 5 - log_2(n) <= a(n) <= 4n - 5 for all n >= 2. More precise bounds are given in the Heinosaari paper.
%e A210532 In the n = 2 case, you need to measure all a(2) = 3 linearly independent observables (e.g., the Pauli X, Y, and Z operators) in order to uniquely specify all pure states.
